Jan 12 2005 	reliable budget motel	I've stayed many times over the past decade at the Howard Johnson Express Inn (at 9th and Harrison, formerly known as the Ho Jo Inn). It is a little unusual in that all the rooms are upstairs (2nd &amp; 3rd floors, no elevator) and accessed via a locking gate from the parking area, which is right next to the little office. It's really a tiny and unconventionally laid-out place, with maybe two dozen rooms. All rooms are accessed via outdoor corridors, but these are behind the locked gate and thus presumably safer than the rooms at the Best Western across the street. I don't worry about safety in this area any more than in any other part of town. It's fine during the day but perhaps a bit spooky in the wee hours of the morning, if one is not used to urban areas.The rooms were remodeled 4-5 years ago and are still in pretty good shape. The baths have attractive, polished ceramic tile floors. The tub and commode are fairly nice for a budget hotel. The sink is outside the bath, part of a counter area that has a mini fridge and microwave, as well as a small drip coffee maker. The TV is large and the cable service has a good assortment of channels. Watch out for the in-room phone service, as rather high per minute toll rates can be charged even if one dials a 415 exchange (without a 1 prefix) that is only a few miles away. Check the location of the dialed number carefully, or use a calling card.Bedding and room furnishings are otherwise about what one should expect for $70-$80 in SF. In general things are in good shape and clean appearing.The person on duty appears to live in a two level suite that connects with the office. For several years the same guy, &quot;Bob&quot; would always be the one to greet me when I checked in, regardless of time of day or day of the week. (I always wondered if he was being held prisoner there!) However Bob seems to have disappeared recently. Nonetheless, my encounters with the staff and housekeeping have always been pleasant here.Parking is free but there are only about 8 or 9 parking spaces; one of those is marked for handicapped use. My experience is that one can usually get a space if one arrives by early evening. Later at night on a weekend would likely be a problem. However, one can park in front of the hotel on the street (metered space) as long as one gets up by 8 AM to feed the meter.This is really a very good choice if one is on a budget, and there really isn't a much better alternative hotel on this side of 5th and Market.	
